                           ³HOW TO PLAY SHADOW WARRIOR³
                           ÀÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÙ


This section will give you general guidelines on how to play Shadow Warrior.
Due to limitations of this document, pictures of the various objects and menus
cannot be provided.  If you have the registered version of Shadow Warrior,
please consult your manual for more detailed information, as well as for some
example pictures.


þ STARTING A NEW GAME

  To start a game of Shadow Warrior, you need to go to your Shadow Warrior game
  directory and type "SW" (without the quotation marks).  Once at the Main
  Menu, select "New Game" to start a game.  If you want to learn how to start a
  multi-player game, please see the section of this file titled, "How to Set Up
  & Play a Network (or Modem/Serial) Game".  Remember, you can press F7 right
  now to bring up the table of contents, which will let you jump to any part of
  this file.
  Once you've selected "New Game", you will be prompted for the name of the
  episode you wish to play.  Once you make your selection, you will be prompted
  to choose a difficulty level.  You can choose from four different difficulty
  levels:

  1) Tiny Grasshopper - The easiest mode.  Few enemies and lots of stuff.
  2) I Have No Fear   - Normal difficulty.
  3) Who Wants Wang   - The Default Setting.  For Experienced Players.
  4) No Pain No Gain  - For Experts Only.  Loads of enemies!

  Once you've made your selection, the game will load.

þ CONTROLLING LO WANG

  After you are in the game, you have many different keys that control Lo Wang.
  You can get a complete listing of the default keys by pressing the F1 key
  during gameplay.  Some of the basic controls used to play Shadow Warrior are:

  Arrows -> Move LoWang ³ Shift    -> Run      ³ 1 to 0 -> Weapons
  A      -> Jump        ³ CapsLock -> AutoRun  ³ Tab    -> Map
  Z      -> Duck        ³ Ctrl     -> Fire     ³ [ or ] -> Inventory Select
  Alt    -> Strafe      ³ Spacebar -> Open/Use ³ Enter  -> Use Inventory Item

  You can also look up and down by pressing Page Up or Page Down.  Using the
  Home and End keys aims up or down. You can use "U" to turn on a mouse aiming
  control system, and "I" to turn on crosshairs for aiming.

  There are more options than these:  press F1 during gameplay to see a
  complete listing of all default controls.  Any of these controls can be
  altered to whatever you want them to be by selecting the "Controller Setup"
  option in the setup program.  Please see the section on "Advanced Controller
  Setup for information regarding controlling your controller.

þ THE STATUS BAR

  During game play, the status bar at the bottom of the screen reveals plenty
  of info.  If you cannot see the status bar on your screen, please use the +
  and - keys to resize it (Press F1 in game for more info). Here is a
  description of all the items in the status bar, from left to right:

  HEALTH  - Shows Lo Wang's health level.  If this drops to zero, you're dead.
  ARMOR   - Shows the percentage of Lo Wang's armor that is left.
  WEAPONS - Shows the status of Lo Wang's weapons.  For each weapon, there are
            two numbers seperated by a /.  The first number is the amount of
            ammo you have for that weapon, and the second is the max amount of
            ammo possible for that weapon.  If the numbers are brightly lit,
            this means it is the currently selected weapon.  If it is of
            medium brightness, it means you have the weapon, but it is not
            currently selected.  If it is dark, it means you have not found
            that weapon yet.
  AMMO    - Shows the amount of ammo left for the currently selected weapon.
  INV     - Shows the percentage and status (if applicable) of the currently
            selected inventory item.  To change the currently selected item,
            use either the [ or ] key.
  KEYS    - Shows the keys currently in your possession.  Keys are required to
            unlock certain doors in the game.  For example, the red key will
            not open a yellow locked door, it will only open a red locked door.

þ LO WANG'S WEAPONS
  There are several weapons Lo Wang can have in his arsenal.  All of them
  will be listed here.  Pressing the number of the weapon (using the top row
  of your keyboard) during game play will activate that weapon, unless you
  don't have it or have run out of ammo for it.  Weapons 8 through 10 are only
  available in the registered version of Shadow Warrior.  Each of these weapons
  can be recharged with ammo found scattered around the levels.  Each weapon
  has its own type of ammo.  For example, if you find a Riot Gun ammo clip,
  you cannot use it with the Missile Launcher.

  1) Fist/Sword - These are the default weapons, and both share the same key,
     that being 1.   You can never run out of "ammo" for your fist or your
     sword, but they're nowhere near as effective as the other weapons in
     the game.  NOTE: There is a secret attack mode for the fists when
     used with a certain inventory item for stealth.

  2) Shuriken - Small hand held "stars" that you throw at enemies.
                Pick Up ammo, you get 9 shurikens, up to a max of 99
                You throw three at a time.
                You must have 3 or more in your possession to use.

  3) Riot Gun - Quad barrel shotgun.
                Picking up weapon gets you 8 shotshells; max of 52.
                Picking up ammo drum gets 24 shotshells
                Weapon has an autofire mode, press "3" again to alternate
                between autofire and standard mode.

  4) UZI Submachine Gun - Fast firing machine gun.
                          Picking up weapon gets you 50 bullets; max of 200
                          Picking up ammo clip gets you 50 bullets
                          If you pick up a second UZI, you can wield two
                          at the same time, John Woo style.

  5) Missile Launcher / Heat Seeker / Nuke
                        Picking up weapon gets 5 missiles; max of 50
                        Picking up ammo pack gets you 5 missiles.
                        This weapon has three modes, press "5" to alternate.
                        (See the "Heat Card" description in the REGULAR GAME
                        ITEMS section a few pages down for more info on this)
                        The third mode will activate the Nuke.  Don't be
                        near it when it goes off.

  6) Grenade Launcher:
                        Picking Up Weapon gets you 6 shells; max of 50
                        Picking up ammo box gets you 8 shells

  7) Sticky Bombs - Small bombs that stick to enemies, walls, you, and
                    many other objects in the environment!
                    Picking up a box of sticky bombs gives you 5 of them,
                    you can have a max of 20 at once.

               THERE ARE MORE WEAPONS IN THE REGISTERED VERSION!
            PLEASE CHECK YOUR REGISTERED GAME MANUAL FOR MORE INFO.

     NOTE: During a Multi-Player game, if you or your friends die, the dead
           player will sometimes drop their currently selected weapon.  If
           this weapon is picked up, all the ammo that was in that weapon will
           transferred to whomever picked it up.  The amount of ammo obtained
           from such a weapon pickup depends on how much ammo the player had
