      cannot help if you do not provide us with the information requested.

þ 3D Realms strongly recommends that you consult your hardware and software
  manuals for your system before you make any suggested changes to your current
  system setup.  Your manuals will tell you if you are about to make changes
  that may irreparably alter your computer or its configuration. Modifying your
  system or software can be dangerous if not done properly. 3D Realms will not
  be able to assist you with any problems resulting from such modifications.

þ If you get an error that has the words "Granular Limit Error" in it, you'll
  have to try booting clean.  Info on "booting clean" is elsewhere in this
  document. The only other thing it could be is some sort of configuration
  setting in your BIOS, but unfortunately, we cannot recommend ideas for this,
  as Granular Limit error is an extremely common problem.

  The only other solution would be if you have a Ensoniq sound card.  If you
  do, and get Granular Limit errors, it usually means that your sound card
  drivers are not correctly installed.

þ If you get random lockups, look at the contents of your config.sys file.
  Look and see if a line similar to this appears: "device=emm386.exe noems".
  If the noems appears, remove it.  Also, if you are using an alternate
  memory manager such as QEMM, make sure it is providing EMS services.

þ If you have a NexGen/586 CPU/Motherboard, you most likely can't get the game
  running.  Try going into your CMOS and look for a setting called "Alternate
  Instructions".  If it is set to OFF, set it to ON. If this doesn't work,
  NexGen has a fix on their World Wide Web site called the Q87 floating point
  emulator.  Their Web site can be reached at http://www.nexgen.com.

þ If you get the error "Exec Error: No such file or directory", it's likely you
  have selected the controller configuration "Keyboard and External".  Go back
  and reconfigure your controller.  Do not select the "External" controller
  unless you have a controller or a device that specifically tells you that you
  need to select this.

þ If you are using the Build editor that comes with the registered CD-ROM, and
  you cannot correctly use the 3D mode, make sure to copy the contents of the
  \goodies\build directory to the directory you have Shadow Warrior installed
  to.  Build cannot be run from a different directory than the game itself.

  Also, when you copy the files, DO NOT USE WINDOWS TO COPY THEM.  Doing so
  will make the resultant copy read-only, and this will cause further problems.
  MAKE SURE THAT YOU COPY THE FILES MANUALLY YOURSELF IN MS-DOS.  Make sure
  that your Build files are not marked read only.  This will cause problems.

þ If you run the game, and get an error that says "Cache Size of zero", or get
  an error that three zeros in it, you most likely have a bad/altered/corrupt
  SW.GRP file.  Check the size of the file on your HD vs the one in the
  \swinst directory on the CD-ROM.  If it is incorrect, MANUALLY COPY THE
  FILE yourself in DOS (do not use Windows).

þ Help!  My directories are gone after playing Shadow Warrior! Check your DOS
  environment. Type "SET" at the command line, and if it looks abnormal,
  reboot. Specifically, you're looking for the DOS environment variable
  DIRCMD. Try entering "SET DIRCMD=", and all should be OK.

þ If you get a message saying "Invalid OpCode", it means you are most likely
  running the game on a 386 computer.  It will not be possible to get around
  this, Shadow Warrior was not designed to run on 386 or 486 computers.  Our
  listed minimum for Shadow Warrior is a Pentium.

þ If you are playing the game, and cannot get the RTS sounds to work, you need
  to make sure you haven't turned "Kid Mode" on.  If Kid Mode is on, the RTS
  system will not work.

